  abstract = {We present constraints on cosmological parameters using number counts as a function of redshift for a sub-sample of 189 galaxy clusters from the Planck SZ (PSZ) catalogue. The PSZ is selected through the signature of the Sunyaev--Zeldovich (SZ) effect, and the sub-sample used here has a signal-to-noise threshold of seven, with each object confirmed as a cluster and all but one with a redshift estimate. We discuss the completeness of the sample and our construction of a likelihood analysis. Using a relation between mass \$M\$ and SZ signal \$Y\$ calibrated to X-ray measurements, we derive constraints on the power spectrum amplitude \$$\backslash$sigma\_8\$ and matter density parameter \$$\backslash$Omega\_\{$\backslash$mathrm\{m\}\}\$ in a flat \$$\backslash$Lambda\$CDM model. We test the robustness of our estimates and find that possible biases in the \$Y\$--\$M\$ relation and the halo mass function are larger than the statistical uncertainties from the cluster sample. Assuming the X-ray determined mass to be biased low relative to the true mass by between zero and 30\%, motivated by comparison of the observed mass scaling relations to those from a set of numerical simulations, we find that \$$\backslash$sigma\_8=0.75$\backslash$pm 0.03\$, \$$\backslash$Omega\_\{$\backslash$mathrm\{m\}\}=0.29$\backslash$pm 0.02\$, and \$$\backslash$sigma\_8($\backslash$Omega\_\{$\backslash$mathrm\{m\}\}/0.27)\^\{0.3\} = 0.764 $\backslash$pm 0.025\$. The value of \$$\backslash$sigma\_8\$ is degenerate with the mass bias; if the latter is fixed to a value of 20\% we find \$$\backslash$sigma\_8($\backslash$Omega\_\{$\backslash$mathrm\{m\}\}/0.27)\^\{0.3\}=0.78$\backslash$pm 0.01\$ and a tighter one-dimensional range \$$\backslash$sigma\_8=0.77$\backslash$pm 0.02\$. We find that the larger values of \$$\backslash$sigma\_8\$ and \$$\backslash$Omega\_\{$\backslash$mathrm\{m\}\}\$ preferred by Planck's measurements of the primary CMB anisotropies can be accommodated by a mass